one:OE.one:T: Sudden sensorineural hearing loss: acute hearing loss that is (1) sensorineural in nature (rather than only due to conduction), (2) within 72hr period, (3) at least 30dB over x3 consecutive test frequencies**
G | Etiology: Most often idiopathic but certain identifiable causes (7-45% of cases), only listing x3 here
G | Pathophysiology: Many theories, most widely accepted are:
Mostly unilateral, typically noticed it after awakening
Most unilateral presentations (>90%) have associated ipsilateral tinnitus
MRI in causes with obvious causes
Oral or intratympanic glucocorticoids (ideally within 2 weeks, may be extended to 6-8 weeks after onset)
Treatment for underlying cause if identified
Spontaneously resolves in 45-65% of cases (or at least some recovery)
Most important prognostic indicator is degree of hearing loss; More mild = more likely to recover
Isolated high- or low-frequency hearing loss (compared with a flat pattern hearing loss across all frequencies) = favourable
Among those with frequency-restricted hearing loss, isolated low-frequency compared with high-frequency hearing loss = favourable
